Date: 9 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Canada - Health Canada SARS website [edited]
[A] Update 25 - Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome 9 Apr 2003 4:00 PM
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/english/protection/warnings/sars/update25.html>

As of 9 Apr 2003, Health Canada has received reports of 242 probable or
suspect cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in Canada. There
have been 10 deaths in Canada. All Canadian cases have occurred in persons
who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS cases in the household
or in a health-care setting. The information contained in this update is
based on the best available information Health Canada has at this time.
The details of the cases to date are as follows:
Ontario is reporting 94 probable and 101 suspect cases. All cases have
occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting.
British Columbia is reporting 3 probable and 31 suspect cases.
New Brunswick is reporting 2 suspect cases.
Saskatchewan is reporting 1 suspect case.
Alberta is reporting 6 suspect cases.
Prince Edward Island is reporting 4 suspect cases.
So far, 49 people have been discharged from hospitals in Ontario. These
people were treated as suspect cases or as probable cases.
These numbers are accurate as of 1:00 PM EDST 9 Apr 2003.
[B] Summary of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) Cases (epidemiology)
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030409_e.html>

Since yesterday, 3 additional probable cases of SARS have been reported in
Canada. A total of 97 individuals who meet the probable case definition of
SARS have been reported in Ontario and British Columbia, including 10
deaths; 144 individuals who meet the definition of a suspect case of SARS
have also been reported in British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan,
Ontario, New Brunswick and Prince Edward Island. Since SARS is a diagnosis
of exclusion, the status of a reported case may change over time.
At the present time, the case fatality rate in Canada is estimated at
approximately 4.1 percent of probable or suspect cases (10 of 241 probable
or suspect cases). Most of the case fatalities occurred in patients with
underlying illness, and nearly all were elderly patients over the age of 70
years.

Table 1: Cumulative Number of SARS Cases Reported in Canada: 9 Apr 2003
Province/Territory: No. probable cases(1)/ No. suspected cases(1)/ Deaths(2)
British Columbia 3/ 31/ 0
Alberta: 0/ 5/ 0
Saskatchewan: 0/ 1/ 0
Ontario: 94/ 101/ 10
New Brunswick: 0/ 2/ 0
Prince Edward Island: 0/ 4/ 0
Total: 97/ 144/ 10
(1)These persons may drop off the probable or suspect case list if another
cause if identified for their illness
(2)This figure is included in the number of probable cases
A summary of the current status of probable cases of SARS in Canada as of 9
Apr 2003 is presented in Table 2. 22 individuals have been discharged (23.9
percent) and of the 60 individuals currently hospitalised, 39 (65 percent)
are improving or in stable condition. In addition, nearly all of the
suspect cases reported in Ontario, British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan,
New Brunswick and Prince Edward Island have either recovered or are
presently recovering.
Table 2: Currently reported status of probable cases of SARS in Canada: 9
Apr 2003
(n=92, excluding 5 for whom status is unknown)
Current status: Number of probable cases/ proportion
Discharged(1): 22/ 23.9 percent
Hospitalised: 60/ 65.2 percent
- Improving (9) (15.0 percent)
- Stable (30) (50.0 percent)
- Critical/Deteriorating (7) (11.7 percent)
- Unknown (14) (23.3 percent)
Deceased 10 10.9 percent
Total number of probable cases with known status, currently hospitalised or
discharged: 92/ 100 percent
(1) Includes cases who have either recovered or are recovering
The current number of probable cases by reported symptom onset date and
type of exposure is provided below (Figure).
[see webpage
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030409_e.html>
for epidemiologic curve of the Number of probable cases of SARS in Canada
by symptom onset date and exposure type from: 23 Feb 2003 to 9 Apr 2003
(n=76, excluding 21 for whom data is pending)
There is currently no evidence to suggest the presence of community
transmission of SARS in Canada. All identified probable cases of SARS have
been linked to either travel-related exposures, or in healthcare and
household settings (Table 3). The index case in Ontario was an individual
who travelled to Hong Kong and stayed at the Metropole Hotel, where a
cluster of SARS cases was subsequently identified (MMWR Vol 52, No. 12, 28
Mar 2003) . Upon return to Canada, disease transmission occurred in 4
members of the immediate and extended family, and nearly all subsequently
identified probable cases in Ontario have been epidemiologically linked to
exposure to the first hospitalised family member of the index case. Other
probable cases reported in Ontario as well as British Columbia have all
been attributed to travel-related exposures. Thus, there is currently no
evidence to suggest that community transmission is occurring in Canada.
Table 3: Type of exposure to probable cases of SARS in Canada: 9 Apr 2003
Exposure: Number of probable cases/ proportion
Hospital or healthcare-related setting: 70/ 72.1 percent
Household: 20/ 20.6 percent
Travel: 7/ 7.2 percent
Total number of probable cases with known exposure: 97/ 100 percent
As part of the public health measures currently being implemented, the
Ontario Ministry of Health and Long-Term Care have identified the following
potential at-risk exposures(1):
- The Scarborough Hospital, Grace Division, between 16--26 Mar 2003
- York Central Hospital in Richmond Hill, between 16--28 Mar 2003
- The Brookside/Hilltop Retirement Residence in Richmond Hill, between
26--29 Mar 2003
- Highland Funeral Home, evening of 3 Apr 2003
(1) The Centenary site of the Rouge Valley Health System (formerly
Scarborough Centenary Hospital) is no longer being identified as a
potential at-risk exposure.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A review of the epidemiologic curve presented as part of this report
reveals the most recent date of onset of a probable case was 2 Apr 2003,
representing 7 days since the onset of the last case. The shape of the
epidemic curve suggests that the outbreak peaked during the period 17-22
Mar 2003 with a second small peak during the period 24-29 Mar 2003. Until
2 incubation periods since the date of onset of the last case has passed,
it would be premature to state definitively that transmission has been
interrupted. - Mod.MPP]
