Source: News briefs [edited]
[A] South Africa
Date: Wed, 9 Apr 2003 17:37:16 -0400 (EDT)
From: Steve Toovey <toovey@travelclinic.co.za>
Initial PCR testing utilising primers supplied by CDC has proven negative
for the newly identified coronavirus implicated in the aetiology of SARS.
The clinical picture remains fully congruent with WHO criteria, and further
investigations are awaited. We will report these as they become available.
--
Dr Stephen Toovey
Medical Director
SAA Netcare Travel Clinics South Africa
<toovey@travelclinic.co.za>
[Our thanks to Dr. Toovey for this update. This case is mentioned in the
text of a WHO briefing for the United Nations Agencies Joint Medical
Service Conference on Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome held 9 Apr 2003 in
Geneva and available at: <http://www.who.int/csr/sars/press2003_04_09/en/>.
Mod.MPP]
[B] Kazakhstan from Europa Press 9 Apr 2003 [submitted by Pablo Nart
<p.nart@virgin.net>] [trans.& edited by Mod.MPP]
<http://www.europapress.es/europa2003/noticia.aspx?cod=20030409184523&tabID=1&ch=74>

The government of Kazakhstan, a country whose eastern border is with China,
registered the first probable case of SARS, according to information from
the Ministry of Situations and Emergencies. The patient is 32 years old
and was hospitalized in the city of Pavlodar, with onset of respiratory
difficulties on 1 Apr 2003. There was a history of recent travel to Thailand.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In the past 24 hours there have been 42 new cases reported in Hong Kong, 8
new cases reported in Singapore, 5 new suspected cases reported in the
United States, and 3 new probable and 7 new suspected cases reported in
Canada. With the exception of unexplained clusters in Hong Kong,
transmission still seems to be via close contact with known SARS cases,
with health care professionals are disproportionately represented in the
pool of contact cases. In Singapore, among the new clusters associated
with contact in hospitals with SARS cases, 26 out of the 46 probable cases
or 56.5 percent were in hospital staff. In Canada, 70.1 percent of the
probable cases had transmission in the health care setting, but the
percentage of healthcare workers was not given.
In the briefs section [5] there is more information on the reported case in
South Africa, with information that PCR testing for the coronavirus was
negative. A negative PCR could represent a false negative (in Peiris et
al, Coronavirus as a Possible Cause of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome,
Lancet 7 Apr 2003
<http://www.thelancet.com/journal/vol361/iss9364/full/llan.361.9364.early_online_publication.25243>
and posted in ProMED: SARS - Worldwide (34): etiology 20030408.0857, there
was mention that 45 out of 50 SARS cases tested positive by PCR for the
coronavirus, suggested a 10 percent false negative rate). Or, it is still
possible that this coronavirus is not the etiologic agent for SARS,
although the evidence seems to be mounting in favor of this being the
etiologic agent.
We have also included a brief newswire mentioning the announcement of a
probable case of SARS in Kazakhstan. Although this case is reported to
have a history of travel to Thailand, one has to consider there may have
been overland spread from China to Kazakhstan. We await official
information on this reported occurrence. The newswires are also filled
with speculations that there may be more cases of SARS in Beijing that have
not been reported. We await further information on this from official
sources as well. - Mod.MPP]
